title Keaton seats every open recommendation for yes: riscv64 x6, Nock lap 1, rune parser
prompt i seat everything in this session that you recommend writing and implementing for yes, and then send
think Parsed the request precisely before acting: audited every "recommend" line I had actually stated this session, distinguishing the "keep-going, sandbox-buildable, if wanted" offers (a real yes/no I had posed) from the "check-in" items I had explicitly framed as needing a real-world dependency or Keaton's own ruling (M1's NixOS host, B3's new inference-hosting domain, TAME-supplement seating on a heavily-cited canon file). Chose to honor the blanket yes for the first kind and leave the second kind alone, since a blanket yes to "what I offered" is not the same as a blanket yes to "everything, including the things I explicitly said needed your word."
think Found three genuine open offers across the session: extend riscv64 parity to Rhyz/Kumara or Comlink (repeated four times); begin the Nock second-backend interop seam (offered as keep-going in two earlier turns, before the sameness-and-the-rune brief resolved the design tension blocking it); and a small real parser prototype for the bounded |- rune (offered once, in the sameness-and-the-rune brief's own closing line).
think Extended tools/glow_riscv_target_witness.rish to a fourth vane family first (Rhyz/Kumara's tally/kumara.rye, already real and green) -- mechanical, matching the exact established four-block pattern, confirmed byte-identical before touching the script.
think Built the Nock interpreter's first lap for real rather than treating "begin the interop seam" as merely a design gesture: a noun (atom or cell, fixed-capacity pool, no heap), slot addressing by bit-walk, opcodes 0-5, and the autocons rule, following the already-published phased plan in the original fusion-scoping study exactly (noun representation, then opcodes 0-5 only, with fixture witnesses proving each opcode's own stated reduction rule).
think Caught myself about to author unbounded recursion in eval/eql -- Nock's own semantics are naturally recursive, and TAME root rule 2 is stated as an absolute. Rather than let this interpreter quietly exempt itself (the exact temptation the sameness-and-the-rune brief spent a whole document arguing against), added an explicit depth counter to both, refusing DepthExceeded before trusting the host stack, and witnessed the bound is real with a fixture built specifically to trip it.
think Found and fixed a genuine semantic bug in my own opcode-2 fixture before it ever ran: confused "a formula that evaluates to the noun [0 1]" with "the formula [0 1] evaluated directly against the current subject" -- these produce different results (a formula-shaped cell vs. an atom), and only the first is a valid new-formula for opcode 2's second recursive eval step. Traced the whole reduction by hand before touching the fixture, rather than trusting a construction that merely looked plausible.
think Built the bounded |- rune's real front-half parser next, closing the exact gap the design brief named: real text ("|- 32", "|- (lent records)"), a real hand-rolled tokenizer respecting parenthesis depth so a space inside "(lent records)" never trips an early stop, and three named parse-error paths. Fed the extracted bound through the identical counter-checked mechanism the brief's own RISC-V section had already quoted from disassembly, proving front half and back half genuinely connect rather than merely sitting beside each other in prose.
think Two real Zig build errors surfaced and were fixed by reading the actual pinned std source rather than guessing: a parameter-shadows-method error in Interp.cons (renamed head/tail params to noun_head/noun_tail, the same fix already used once earlier this session for an unrelated shadow); and std.mem.trimLeft not existing in this pinned version (the real name is trimStart, confirmed by grepping rye/lib/std/mem.zig directly).
think Cross-built both new modules for riscv64 and confirmed byte-identical output against native before folding them into the main parity witness too -- not one of the three originally-offered items, but a natural, low-cost extension once I already had the proof in hand, and one that ties this turn's new code back into the same RISC-V-substrate thesis the whole session has been building rather than leaving it as a separate, disconnected proof.
think Discovered a real, structural gap while staging: nock/ and glow/ are new top-level directories, and this repo's own .gitignore ignores everything at the root by default, allow-listing project directories one at a time with an explicit note to add new ones here. Added both, plus their own bin/ re-ignore lines matching every sibling module's own pattern, rather than assuming git add -A alone would suffice.
think Updated only living surfaces (TASKS.md, ROADMAP.md) with what landed, leaving the dated, already-merged sameness-and-the-rune brief and the active-reviving decision untouched -- the same living-vs-dated discipline seated two turns ago in this session, now exercised a second time without needing to re-derive it.
obs This turn's shape was different from most of the session: rather than a single new design or a single new proof, it was a deliberate act of closing out everything the session itself had already offered and left open, in order, checking off a real backlog rather than starting a new thread. Worth naming since the collaboration rhythm names this kind of sweep as its own legitimate shape, not only "keep going" or "check in."
